char.label: It is a fairly robust bone with a well-rounded caput humeri, which is separated from rest of the humerus by a distinct and waisted short shaft, or neck, visible especially on the posterior surface.
A sharp rim delineates the unfinished surface of the caput from the neck.
In posterior view (Fig. 2D-E), the articular area of the caput slopes towards the dorsal surface.
On the distal surface, the radial and ulnar condyles appear to be similar in size, with the size of the radial condyle being underestimated by Long (1989:fig. 11d; Fig. 1A).
These articulation surfaces are both convex and sub-circular, and are aligned although separated by a slight waisting.
The entepicondyle is large and robust, and meets the ulnar condyle at an angle of approximately 130 degrees (Fig. 2B, C).
Unfinished bone of the ulnar condyle is continuous with part of the dorsal ridge as well as with the dorsal edge of the entepicondyle.
A small depression situated dorsally on the entepicondyle, below the neck of the caput humeri, may represent the entepicondylar foramen.
An opening of the entepicondylar foramen may also be present in a shallow groove running along the distal margin of the humerus, just ventral to the ulnar and radial condyles.
In this groove, named here the distal groove, a small, circular depression just ventral to the ulnar condyle may represent the opening of the entepicondylar foramen.
A strong dorsal ridge is present on the dorsal surface between the caput and radial and ulnar condyles.

Distal to the dorsal ridge, between it and the ulnar/radial condyles, is a deep depression with striations for muscle attachments, called the ectepicondylar depression by Long (1989) ('ar.m.sup' of Vorobyeva, 2000) (Fig. 2B, C).
This 'ectepicondylar depression' ends in a V-shape, such that the dorsal ridge converges with the base of the ulnar condyle.

An ectepicondylar ridge, on the opposing posterior surface of the humerus in Strepsodus (Jeffery, 2001:fig. 4g) does not appear to be present, although several low ridges extend distally from the base of the neck of the caput humeri.
An ectepicondyle could be obscured by a crack, seen as a ridge in the cast (Fig. 2B, C).
The humeral ridge, continuous with the entepicondyle, is robust, extensive and becomes thicker away from the entepicondyle (Fig. 2D, E).

Between the dorsal ridge and the caput humeri is a further recessed area, here termed the columnar area (referring to the neck region of the caput humeri; Fig. 2B, C), that clearly separates these two structures and is slightly separated from the dorsal surface of the entepicondyle, and more specifically from the unfinished bone of the entepicondyle, by a narrow ridge (Fig. 2B, C).

The columnar area contains several depressions, one of which was said to provide an attachment area for dorsal muscles from the humerus to the body (Long, 1989:figs. 11a, c, 'scha'; Fig. 1A), specifically, for the scapulohumeralis muscle, running between the scapulocoracoid and humerus (Andrews and Westoll, 1970a; Rackoff, 1980).
The distinct neck separating the caput from the rest of the humerus in Barameda is not as elongate as that illustrated in Strepsodus (Vorobyeva, 2000).

A neck has also been identified in the Lower Carboniferous rhizodontid Rhizodus (Jeffery, 2001). A waisted neck is not present in the Upper Devonian taxa Aztecia (Johanson and Ahlberg, 2001), nor in Sauripterus (Davis et al., 2004).

Such a ridge is present also in Aztecia (Johanson and Ahlberg, 2001) and Sauripterus (Davis et al., 2004), although in these taxa the dorsal ridge is not oriented towards, and does not reach, the ulnar condyle

The distal groove separating the ulnar and radial condyles from the continuous entepicondyle-humeral ridge-pectoral process was figured in Sauripterus (Davis et al., 2004), Strepsodus (Jeffery, 2001) and Rhizodus (Andrews and Westoll, 1970a:pl. 9h) but not named. The distal groove may be deepest in the humerus (MCZ 13880) likened to Strepsodus (Godfrey, 1989). A portion of the distal groove can be seen in Barameda, ventral to the ulnar condyle, but its extent across the entire distal surface of the humerus can only be inferred and we cannot comment about its depth, although it appears shallower near the ulnar condyle.
The presence of a marked ectepicondylar depression in Sauripterus, Barameda, and Rhizodus suggests that it is not crushed, at least in these specimens.
In Rhizodus (Jeffrey, 2001:fig. 3b) this depression separates the dorsal ridge from the ulnar and radial condyles and continues onto the neck of the caput, unlike all other rhizodontids.
The exposed proximal edge is expanded and rounded for articulation with the humerus, while the exposed distal margin is concave and elongate.
The mesial margin is thickest at the proximal end of the radius and becomes thinner distally.

The radius is thus not rod shaped as originally reconstructed by Long (1989:fig. 11a), with approximately only a third of it visible, if its shape was similar to that of other Carboniferous rhizodontids.
When in position it would have been longer and wider then the ulna
The ulna is a rather square, robust, and slightly waisted bone, wider at the distal than the proximal end,
It flares out distally to articulate with the ulnare and intermedium.
The proximal articulation surface on the ulna for the humerus is large and strongly concave, matching the convexity of the corresponding articular surface on the humerus.
The distal articulation surfaces for the ulnare and intermedium are fairly flat, with the facet for the intermedium being wider dorsoventrally.
It is now apparent that the ulna is a little larger than the newly prepared ulnare (described below) but of similar shape.
It is a little smaller than the ulna and broadens distally with articulation surfaces for three distal radials.

Long (1989:fig. 11a; Fig. 1A) was correct in his hypothesised reconstruction of the ulnare articulating distally with three elements. A similar condition is seen in Gooloogongia (Johanson and Ahlberg, 2001) and in the holotype of Sauripterus (AMNH 3341) (Davis et al., 2004). It is probable that the ulnare of the Lower Carboniferous rhizodontid Strepsodus also articulated with three distal radials (Jeffery, 2001
The intermedium of Barameda is longer and narrower than the ulnare and ulna (Figs. 2A, 3A).
It is waisted, flaring out distally to produce two articulation surfaces for distal radials.
There are also pronounced ridges on its dorsal surface that indicate possible muscle attachments.

A single distal radial was described by Long (1989:figs. 11a, b; Fig. 1A) as being hourglass shaped, as long as the intermedium but much narrower, and having two distal articulation surfaces, a condition verified by Sauripterus
There are approximately 40 rows of lepidotrichia on NMV P160885, consisting of proximal, elongate, unjointed basal segments and distal, short, jointed segments (Figs. 2A, 3A).
In casts, the lepidotrichia appear to begin at the level of the distal end of the ulnare and intermedium, partly covering the fourth distal radial, and overlying the third distal radial.
Towards the margin of the fin (= distal frill of Andrews, 1985), the elongate segments end and the fin rays continue as jointed lepidotrichia (
All of the individual segments are hourglass-shaped

The structure of individual distal segments is more complex (Fig. 3C,D3-5) than the unjointed proximal segments, which appear to be rounded in section and slightly expanded where they meet the jointed segments of the distal frill.

Each jointed segment is exposed in at least three aspects, with one face buried. The exposed faces consist of marked longitudinal ridges around a central core, so that they resemble mammalian caudal vertebrae (Fig. 3C,D3-5).

In at least some of the lepidotrichia the proximal end of each segment is convex and the distal end concave, reflecting the shape of the ends of the endochondral limb elements such as the ulnare and intermedium.

At the level where the fin rays become jointed, some of the unjointed segments taper in thickness and some branch just before the frill of jointed lepidotrichia (Fig. 3C,D2); branching also occurs in the segments within this frill.
Segmented lepidotrichia have been reported in Strepsodus (Andrews, 1973, 1985; Jeffery, 2001), Screbinodus (Andrews, 1973, 1985), Gooloogongia (Johanson and Ahlberg, 2001)
Barameda and Gooloogongia may be the only rhizodonts in which some branching of the elongate basal segments does occur.
Reinterpretation of NMV P160885 indicates that, while the pectoral fin is long, it is not narrow (Fig. 3B).
This suggests that the fin fanned out and would have been paddle-shaped.
What appears to be most of the concave glenoid fossa of the scapulocoracoid is preserved in close association with the caput humeri (Figs. 1B, 2A, 3A).

However, the overall fin flexibility in rhizodonts would be reduced by the arrangement of the larger elements of the fin, where the articulation between the radius and the distal radials is more proximal and offset relative to the articulation between the ulnare/intermedium and their associated distal radials.
In other words, the transverse joints between the endochondral elements of the fin are not continuous across the width of the fin resulting in a fin that was more stiffened proximally.
